<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp2sec4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Congruences</title>

  <p> </p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-congruence">
    <title>Congruence</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If  <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> are integers and <m> m </m> is a positive integer, then <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> are <term>congruent modulo</term> <m> m </m>, written <m> a \equiv b \pmod m</m>, if <m> m \mid (a-b)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-congruence_is_equivalence_relation">
  <title>Congruence is an Equivalence Relation</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b,c,m\in \Z</m> where <m>m&gt;0</m>, then
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>a \equiv a \pmod m</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a \equiv b \pmod m</m>, then <m>b \equiv a \pmod m</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a \equiv b \pmod m</m> and <m>b \equiv c \pmod m</m>, then <m>a \equiv c \pmod m</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proof.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-divisibility_is_transitive"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<proposition xml:id="proposition-congruence_preserves_operations">
  <title>Congruence Preserves Operations</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b,a',b'\in \Z</m> where <m>m&gt;0</m> and <m>a \equiv a' \pmod m</m> and <m>b \equiv b' \pmod m</m>, then
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>a+b \equiv a' + b' \pmod m</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>ab \equiv a'b' \pmod m</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

    </p>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b,a',b'\in \Z</m> where <m>m&gt;0</m>, then
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a \equiv a' \pmod m</m> and <m>b \equiv b' \pmod m</m>, then <m>a + b \equiv a' + b' \pmod m</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a \equiv a' \pmod m</m> and <m>b \equiv b' \pmod m</m>, then <m>ab \equiv a'b' \pmod m</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proof.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-congruence_is_equivalence_relation"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

  <definition xml:id="definition-least_residue">
    <title>Least Residue</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If  <m> a </m>  and <m> m </m> are integers and <m> m </m> is a positive integer, the unique <m> r </m> from the division algorithm such that <m>a=qm+r</m> and <m>0\le r &lt; m</m> is called the <term>least residue</term> of <m>a</m> modulo <m> m </m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-congruence_and_least_residue">
  <title>Congruence and Least Residue</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>m\in \Z</m> is positive, then two integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are congruent modulo <m>m</m> if and only if they have the same least residue modulo <m>m</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  First suppose two integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> have the same least residue modulo <m>m</m>.  Write down the expressions and analyze.  Why are they congruent modulo <m>m</m>?  Next suppose the integers are congruent modulo <m>m</m> and let <m>r</m> be the least residue of one of them.  Why must the other have the same least residue modulo <m>m</m>?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, <xref ref="definition-least_residue"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, and  <xref ref="proposition-congruence_preserves_operations"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>  

<proposition xml:id="proposition-congruence_cancellation_theorem">
  <title>Cancellation Theorem for Congruences</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,m\in \Z</m> are positive relatively prime integers and <m>x,y,\in \Z</m>, then <m>ax \equiv ay \pmod m</m> implies <m>x \equiv y \pmod m</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Try rewriting the congruence.  What is <m>ax - ay</m> congruent to?  Why?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, <xref ref="definition-relatively_prime"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-congruence_preserves_operations"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>



</section>